      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 21:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Now known as ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "El-Jib",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", a commanding eminence (as the name implies) some six miles north of Jerusalem. Strictly, it consists of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "two",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " heights, on one of which, it is conjectured, the town stood, while the other was the high place. Solomon was accompanied to Gibeon by \"all the congregation,\" including the captains, judges, governors, etc. (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 1:2, 3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "to sacrifice there",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " [This religious service was designed to inaugurate his reign (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 1:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), after the precedent of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 11:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 6:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". His object was also to supplicate the Divine blessing on his undertakings. If his visit served at the same time as a farewell, or \"honourable funeral to the tabernacle\" (Wordsw.) this was an accident]; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "for that was the great high place",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " [being the place of the tabernacle and brazen altar. In ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 21:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " we find the tabernacle at Nob, though without the ark (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 4:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). After the massacre of the priests it lost the ephod (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 22:20",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 23:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). It could hardly remain in a spot stained by so much blood; but how or when it found its way to Gibeon, we do not know. See ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 16:37, 39",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 1:3-6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "]: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "a thousand burnt offerings",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " [such numbers were not infrequent at festivals. See on 1 Kings 8:62, and cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 29:33, 34",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Rawlinson reminds us that \"Xerxes offered 1000 oxen at Troy\" (Herod. 7:43).] ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "did Solomon offer",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " [not, of course, personally, as some (Ewald. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "e.g.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
